column23: The evaluation script was able to compile your submission into the
executable pa5.
If there is an attachment CE_log.txt, it means that there were warning
messages from the compiler.  You should pay attention to all the warning
messages to make sure that it is indeed your intention to program in such a
way that you have these warnings.   If your work does not work as intended
(see the feedback included in the attached grade_log.csv), fixing these
warnings may sometimes eliminate these unpredictable behaviors.
The attached grade_log.csv should be viewed as a spreadsheet.
The first column contains the names of the test cases.  The remaining columns
are as follows:
timeout: 0 if your program completed its execution within the time limit
1 otherwise
time(sec): the actual runtime of your program if it completed the test case
within the time limit
-1 otherwise
nrows: the number of rows in example
ncols: the number of cols in example
min time: the smallest fastest time among the ncols entries
max time: the largest fastest time among the ncols entries
table file: -1, cannot be opened (output 1)
0, can be opened but wrong format (based on the example)
1, can be opened and correct format (based on the example)
Even if the format is correct for a 3*4 table,
if the input is a 30*40 table, it will report the format to be
incorrect
valid table entries: The number of entries that match the example (should
be (nrows * ncols + 2), 2 entries to specifies the nrows
ncols, and the others to fill the table
0 if table file cannot be opened
time file: -1, cannot be opened (output 2)
0, can be opened but wrong format
1, can be opened and correct format
valid times: The number of entries that are correct (should be ncols)
0 if time file cannot be opened
path file: -1, cannot be opened (output 3)
0, can be opened but wrong format
1, can be opened and correct format
reported time: the fastest time reported by student (INT_MAX if path file not
present)
evaluated time: the fastest time evaluated by the grading script based on
the path in the path file (INT_MAX if invalid path)
a fastest path: 1 if it is a fastest path (not necessary the min fastest path,
for that, you have to compare the evaluated time and the
min time)
0 otherwise
Used memory (bytes): amount of memory used by your program
-1 when your program timed out, seg fault or stack overflow
Stack overflow: 0 if no overflow
non-zero (timed out, segmentation fault, or actual overflow)
Memory leak: 0 if no memory leak
non-zero (timed out or actual memory leak)
Memory error: 0 if no memory error
non-zero (timed out or actual memory error)
